tal-interpretability" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">We&#39;re interested in comparing models across time to understand how they develop</a>. High-level observables like the local learning coefficient give us insight into this process without requiring a detailed understanding of the model&#39;s internal mechanisms. </p><p>In particular, we&#39;re aiming to understand phase transitions during learning — moments in which models go through sudden, unanticipated shifts. We want to be able to detect these transitions because we think most of the risk is contained in sudden, undesired changes to values or capabilities that occur during training (~sharp left turns) and sudden, undesired changes to behaviors that occur in-context (treacherous turns / mechanistic anomalies).</p><p>Local learning coefficient estimation is one of the first steps towards building tools for detecting and understanding these transitions. </p><p><strong>Do phase transitions actually show up? </strong>So far, the places where theoretically predicted phase transitions are easiest to confirm are simplified settings like <a href="https://arxiv.org/pdf/1312.6120.pdf" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">deep linear networks </a>and <a href="https://transformer-circuits.pub/2022/toy_model/index.html" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">toy models of superposition</a>. For larger models, we expect phase transitions to be common but &#34;hidden.&#34; Among our <a href="https://www.lesswrong.com/posts/TjaeCWvLZtEDAS5Ex/towards-developmental-interpretability" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">immediate priorities</a> are testing just how common these transitions are and whether we can detect hidden transitions.</p><p><strong>Deep linear networks. </strong>Let&#39;s consider the example of deep linear networks (DLNs). These are neural networks without nonlinear activations. In terms of expressivity, these models are identical to a simple affine transformation but in terms of dynamics they&#39;re much more interesting. The observed <a href="https://browse.arxiv.org/pdf/2106.15933.pdf" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">&#34;saddle-to-saddle&#34; transitions</a> involve sudden jumps in the loss that coincide with sudden increases in the learning coefficient. </p><figure><img src="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/FX510iWLYv_cE9ZR70TiSdFofyIicpqiIBWDrDEYeB8=/aHR0cHM6Ly9yZXMuY2xvdWRpbmFyeS5jb20vbGVzc3dyb25nLTItMC9pbWFnZS91cGxvYWQvZl9hdXRvLHFfYXV0by92MS9taXJyb3JlZEltYWdlcy82ZzhjQWZ0ZlF1ZkxtRkRZVC9paWZsbGhzaG9pNndnb2JybHk4YQ==" srcset="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/apo1i4qESqblCpMSSxhIxuICi42ZvxR3ViVgJeKJuj8=/aHR0cHM6Ly9yZXMuY2xvdWRpbmFyeS5jb20vbGVzc3dyb25nLTItMC9pbWFnZS91cGxvYWQvZl9hdXRvLHFfYXV0by92MS9taXJyb3JlZEltYWdlcy82ZzhjQWZ0ZlF1ZkxtRkRZVC9uZW0xb2N5dHg4emgycnQ4NGprag== 132w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/m_M2HFvAbakCO263QyALMW22jv2LiAFaiwkAO3icDIQ=/aHR0cHM6Ly9yZXMuY2xvdWRpbmFyeS5jb20vbGVzc3dyb25nLTItMC9pbWFnZS91cGxvYWQvZl9hdXRvLHFfYXV0by92MS9taXJyb3JlZEltYWdlcy82ZzhjQWZ0ZlF1ZkxtRkRZVC9lenFiZHJhbXR3bWRxZWw0N3NrYQ== 212w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/gYepMO2n4m9BZN8AsznxS3jfhV6gkl4BG-6L0fhTVpU=/aHR0cHM6Ly9yZXMuY2xvdWRpbmFyeS5jb20vbGVzc3dyb25nLTItMC9pbWFnZS91cGxvYWQvZl9hdXRvLHFfYXV0by92MS9taXJyb3JlZEltYWdlcy82ZzhjQWZ0ZlF1ZkxtRkRZVC9lZG9tbXd5MTBpenJ1eTRxN2t4MA== 292w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/dsq9Ph_E2oOuu3DbyaOvVeuNkdePPPtOpEtUDAcR2P0=/aHR0cHM6Ly9yZXMuY2xvdWRpbmFyeS5jb20vbGVzc3dyb25nLTItMC9pbWFnZS91cGxvYWQvZl9hdXRvLHFfYXV0by92MS9taXJyb3JlZEltYWdlcy82ZzhjQWZ0ZlF1ZkxtRkRZVC9pMmpkdGxjZnc3Z3Zkc2dncGUxMQ== 372w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/u4SEHzK2jTBLoQ01SDXTyYf-gTNxXxrqgg-Tmtd4frQ=/aHR0cHM6Ly9yZXMuY2xvdWRpbmFyeS5jb20vbGVzc3dyb25nLTItMC9pbWFnZS91cGxvYWQvZl9hdXRvLHFfYXV0by92MS9taXJyb3JlZEltYWdlcy82ZzhjQWZ0ZlF1ZkxtRkRZVC9kZmdxdmc0d3ZvOWZudGppNW1yMQ== 452w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/jNwFGOw0wEyilctulFPhgCCogm7TjY9ZJ727cD5_7fI=/aHR0cHM6Ly9yZXMuY2xvdWRpbmFyeS5jb20vbGVzc3dyb25nLTItMC9pbWFnZS91cGxvYWQvZl9hdXRvLHFfYXV0by92MS9taXJyb3JlZEltYWdlcy82ZzhjQWZ0ZlF1ZkxtRkRZVC90bXJmdTB4MmNtbGIwaTN3ZXN0cQ== 532w" loading="lazy"/><figcaption><a href="https://github.com/timaeus-research/devinterp/blob/main/examples/dlns.ipynb" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">DLNs</a> show sudden increases in model complexity, ^λ (<strong>orange</strong>), coinciding with sudden decreases in loss (<strong>blue</strong>).</figcaption></figure><h1>From Basins to Model Complexity</h1><p>In this section, we&#39;ll motivate the learning coefficient by attempting to formalize a working definition of basin volume (through which we&#39;ll see that what we really care about is basin volume scaling). We&#39;ll see in what sense the learning coefficient measures model complexity and examine the resulting perspective on phase transitions. </p><h2>Intractable: Basin Volume</h2><p><strong>Basin volume and model simplicity. </strong>Learning theorists have long been interested in the link between basin volume and model simplicity. We don&#39;t really care what model we end up with as long as its loss is below some threshold ϵ. This is particularly true as that threshold approaches its minimum: we want to know how many &#34;almost-as-good&#34; solutions there are in the neighborhood of an obtained solution w∗. </p><p>Intuitively, broader basins (with more suitable models) are simpler. Because they take up more volume, they require fewer bits to locate. In accordance with Occam&#39;s razor, we want the simplest possible solution for the problem at hand.<sup><a href="#fn1s1fnajc57s">[1]</a></sup> </p><p><strong>To measure a basin. </strong>In particular, given an upper bound to the loss L(w)≤ϵ, we want to compute the following volume (=&#34;area&#34; in the case of two parameters):</p>V(ϵ)=∫L(w)≤ϵφ(w)dw<p>for some prior φ(w) over weights w. For our purposes, we can safely neglect the prior and treat it as constant. Consider the toy loss landscape below, where V(ϵ) is indicated by the gray projection. </p><figure><img src="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/7AvuJXOy0VJt73AkoPnjlFvDGU155g8D9xJflQTdBnY=/aHR0cHM6Ly9yZXMuY2xvdWRpbmFyeS5jb20vbGVzc3dyb25nLTItMC9pbWFnZS91cGxvYWQvZl9hdXRvLHFfYXV0by92MS9taXJyb3JlZEltYWdlcy82ZzhjQWZ0ZlF1ZkxtRkRZVC90c3NmMWVxeHRubHpmbHI2bm04aQ==" srcset="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/xaI8JyMDu9qgUOGA2fZ4jIbOwkPyB8lOaFu9hurfBRA=/aHR0cHM6Ly9yZXMuY2xvdWRpbmFyeS5jb20vbGVzc3dyb25nLTItMC9pbWFnZS91cGxvYWQvZl9hdXRvLHFfYXV0by92MS9taXJyb3JlZEltYWdlcy82ZzhjQWZ0ZlF1ZkxtRkRZVC9iYWExc2tjbGRqMDJzMHFra3FrMQ== 180w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/tTy4QBD3SEkridL6LS-mxTGbusEW7qQHQME5smdRfSM=/aHR0cHM6Ly9yZXMuY2xvdWRpbmFyeS5jb20vbGVzc3dyb25nLTItMC9pbWFnZS91cGxvYWQvZl9hdXRvLHFfYXV0by92MS9taXJyb3JlZEltYWdlcy82ZzhjQWZ0ZlF1ZkxtRkRZVC9mNG1sd2trNHdybXEwNHJvZDBrcA== 360w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/6d9j8wgkMTGkR7DzVmQtWKZnC0goUuf0QFTt9-bi9TI=/aHR0cHM6Ly9yZXMuY2xvdWRpbmFyeS5jb20vbGVzc3dyb25nLTItMC9pbWFnZS91cGxvYWQvZl9hdXRvLHFfYXV0by92MS9taXJyb3JlZEltYWdlcy82ZzhjQWZ0ZlF1ZkxtRkRZVC92b3IzeXRlemt6emRweXlkd29lMg== 540w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/eV45AcgJDX6c_IqZfrRHJCI3B7A32BU6fskzJm2eJHs=/aHR0cHM6Ly9yZXMuY2xvdWRpbmFyeS5jb20vbGVzc3dyb25nLTItMC9pbWFnZS91cGxvYWQvZl9hdXRvLHFfYXV0by92MS9taXJyb3JlZEltYWdlcy82ZzhjQWZ0ZlF1ZkxtRkRZVC9pYnFrdGwybWlleHdubTVxaGN1eg== 720w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/aCOafkqM3w64_lMIH3m-03NFEt17k8YaOvU0kmJJ2g4=/aHR0cHM6Ly9yZXMuY2xvdWRpbmFyeS5jb20vbGVzc3dyb25nLTItMC9pbWFnZS91cGxvYWQvZl9hdXRvLHFfYXV0by92MS9taXJyb3JlZEltYWdlcy82ZzhjQWZ0ZlF1ZkxtRkRZVC96bmd5dXZ6YWl2YWUxdXpieHE0Mw== 900w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/Pk7To6wdkPx_D0ylBde60-w0pXlhMloUi4GDOu3ah6s=/aHR0cHM6Ly9yZXMuY2xvdWRpbmFyeS5jb20vbGVzc3dyb25nLTItMC9pbWFnZS91cGxvYWQvZl9hdXRvLHFfYXV0by92MS9taXJyb3JlZEltYWdlcy82ZzhjQWZ0ZlF1ZkxtRkRZVC92aGhsbGh6ZGg4enQ2aTdpaWs1bQ== 1080w, https://reader.miniflux.app/pr