er">The standard correction is to add a small constant to these zero eigenvalues</a>, which stabilizes the Hessian. We get a very large volume, instead of an infinite volume. But this misses the point: when second order terms vanish, the qualitative equivalence between a function and its second-order Taylor approximation breaks down, and these Hessian-based approximations become invalid.</p><p>Instead, we need to go to higher order terms in the Taylor expansion. The lowest order contributions to the volume will be dominated by the highest order terms in the expansion. </p><p><strong>Flatness ≠ broadness. </strong>In the literature, flatness (in the sense of a small determinant of the Hessian) and broadness often get conflated. This is unfortunate: the two are not the same. Basin broadness is an interesting question. Minimum flatness is the wrong question. </p><h2>Instead: Basin Dimension</h2><p><strong>Volume dynamics. </strong>We care about relative — not absolute — volumes. But even more importantly, we&#39;re interested in dynamics: how the volume changes as learning progresses. As we gather more and more data, we&#39;re able to become more discriminating and our threshold ϵ comes down. The real question, then, is: how does the volume scale as ϵ changes? This is more relevant even in the non-degenerate regular case.</p><p><strong>Volume scaling &gt; volume. </strong>Studying volume scaling solves several others problems with the volume. First, for sufficiently small ϵ, relative volumes become independent of ϵ, which allows us to eliminate the dependence on this arbitrary cut-off. Furthermore, volume scaling is invariant under reparametrizations and non-diverging even near degenerate critical points.</p><p><strong>The learning coefficient as effective dimensionality.</strong> The volume scales as</p>V(ϵ)∼cϵλasϵ→0.<p>The scaling exponent λ is known as the <strong>learning coefficient</strong> (or &#34;<a href="https://www.lesswrong.com/posts/4eZtmwaqhAgdJQDEg/dslt-1-the-rlct-measures-the-effective-dimension-of-neural" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">real log canonical threshold</a>&#34;). It plays the role of an effective dimensionality (up to a constant multiple).</p><p> Let&#39;s illustrate this with some examples. </p><p><strong>Regular models. </strong>First, consider the case of regular (=non-singular) models, where the loss landscape has no degenerate critical points. In this case, the Hessian-based approximation holds, and the volume grows with exponent λ=d/2, where d is the number of dimensions (or parameter count).</p><figure><img src="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/jeunLVUwsy4jmT9sotrtaISDtc-qnMxZRtqZiORFDM0=/aHR0cHM6Ly9yZXMuY2xvdWRpbmFyeS5jb20vbGVzc3dyb25nLTItMC9pbWFnZS91cGxvYWQvZl9hdXRvLHFfYXV0by92MS9taXJyb3JlZEltYWdlcy82ZzhjQWZ0ZlF1ZkxtRkRZVC9vc29nOHlkYmRrd29na3VnNGxlMQ==" srcset="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/ddRmebk3D1OKqsWXj1PRyCpUq10uHjD5Y555QN3uHXs=/aHR0cHM6Ly9yZXMuY2xvdWRpbmFyeS5jb20vbGVzc3dyb25nLTItMC9pbWFnZS91cGxvYWQvZl9hdXRvLHFfYXV0by92MS9taXJyb3JlZEltYWdlcy82ZzhjQWZ0ZlF1ZkxtRkRZVC94ZHV2ZHp1ZXhtdmh1ZjNycm1sag== 160w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/D6KeJdNB7tG2cYjZUERr4qCCOFanRSfKWIvU9jidv8k=/aHR0cHM6Ly9yZXMuY2xvdWRpbmFyeS5jb20vbGVzc3dyb25nLTItMC9pbWFnZS91cGxvYWQvZl9hdXRvLHFfYXV0by92MS9taXJyb3JlZEltYWdlcy82ZzhjQWZ0ZlF1ZkxtRkRZVC9ubWJmb3ozMGFtdmtqc2JudGNxaQ== 320w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/rthLCzAfSBPNrTAD2Ji3UyRUyF2vVlOnRMsHg2uGmd4=/aHR0cHM6Ly9yZXMuY2xvdWRpbmFyeS5jb20vbGVzc3dyb25nLTItMC9pbWFnZS91cGxvYWQvZl9hdXRvLHFfYXV0by92MS9taXJyb3JlZEltYWdlcy82ZzhjQWZ0ZlF1ZkxtRkRZVC9kNXZrZTFkNG9wbmtoMHB1cGJ6bQ== 480w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/rndVmi6OVnlx2I8_MpYjFRVN8Xv2YnCYrjS_basWf6M=/aHR0cHM6Ly9yZXMuY2xvdWRpbmFyeS5jb20vbGVzc3dyb25nLTItMC9pbWFnZS91cGxvYWQvZl9hdXRvLHFfYXV0by92MS9taXJyb3JlZEltYWdlcy82ZzhjQWZ0ZlF1ZkxtRkRZVC95cGtmcG54cWlpcmZwcmJ6Y2h5ZA== 640w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/wHnyR80r6RpuWlSLbi1iZVPjYSHqJOfEdGzLvzRi-SU=/aHR0cHM6Ly9yZXMuY