ϵ&gt;1 but faster for small ϵ&lt;1. There&#39;s exponentially more volume in the immediate vicinity of degenerate critical points than in the vicinity of non-degenerate critical points. </p><p><strong>Against Hessians. </strong>The two preceding examples explicitly demonstrate the failures of the Hessian mentioned earlier. Their Hessians are identical at the origin, but their scaling behaviors are radically different. The Hessian is a poor judge of volume, and derived metrics like the rank of the Hessian are insufficient notions of model complexity.<sup><a href="#fny3eyq6a3fpf">[2]</a></sup> </p><p><strong>The learning coefficient as an inductive bias. </strong>The Occam&#39;s razor intuition that simpler models (with lower complexity) generalize better is formalized by <a href="http://watanabe-www.math.dis.titech.ac.jp/users/swatanab/ag-slt.html" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">Watanabe&#39;s free energy formula</a>,</p>Fn→nLn(w∗)+λlogn+O(loglogn)asn→∞,<p>where n is the number of training samples, Ln is the loss (more precisely, the negative log likelihood) which depends on a dataset Dn of n samples, and w∗ is an optimal choice of weights.</p><p>A full explanation and derivation of this formula is beyond the scope of this post (see <a href="https://www.lesswrong.com/posts/xRWsfGfvDAjRWXcnG/distilling-singular-learning-theory" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">Liam&#39;s excellent sequence</a>), but the important bit is that we can construe the problem of Bayesian learning as a problem of trying to minimize this free energy, involving a tradeoff between accuracy (lower nLn(w∗)) and complexity (lower λlogn). Neural networks are intrinsically biased towards simpler solutions. </p><p><strong>Intuition for phase transitions. </strong>Consider a toy landscape with two local minima at w1and w2 with heights L(w1)&gt;L(w2). Both minima have an associated learning coefficient that determines how the volume scales in its neighborhood. Suppose λ(w1)&lt;λ(w2). Solution 1 is simpler but with higher loss, and solution 2 is more accurate but also more complex. </p><p>Coming back to the volume for a moment, what happens as we gradually lower the threshold ϵ? </p><figure><img src="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/EanvEqwn6F6oLOTXqU6AJWlbDEVvL4awe3_d7j_Jofs=/aHR0cHM6Ly9yZXMuY2xvdWRpbmFyeS5jb20vbGVzc3dyb25nLTItMC9pbWFnZS91cGxvYWQvZl9hdXRvLHFfYXV0by92MS9taXJyb3JlZEltYWdlcy82ZzhjQWZ0ZlF1ZkxtRkRZVC9idWNqY25zdmRoeW5zMXBuY2F1Zg==" srcset="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/CTBz3FKBGF5rzG-FaWk8Gz19wDxRqResovoPwSNFVyU=/aHR0cHM6Ly9yZXMuY2xvdWRpbmFyeS5jb20vbGVzc3dyb25nLTItMC9pbWFnZS91cGxvYWQvZl9hdXRvLHFfYXV0by92MS9taXJyb3JlZEltYWdlcy82ZzhjQWZ0ZlF1ZkxtRkRZVC9raGtkeWFrbnFrbXozcmR4cWhqdg== 120w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/hnhQ0cLuS7edI-hm4zbIIpF12CyUQLeMbA6xkgOS6Vo=/aHR0cHM6Ly9yZXMuY2xvdWRpbmFyeS5jb20vbGVzc3dyb25nLTItMC9pbWFnZS91cGxvYWQvZl9hdXRvLHFfYXV0by92MS9taXJyb3JlZEltYWdlcy82ZzhjQWZ0ZlF1ZkxtRkRZVC93aWl4eGJvdDR2emNsZXZqNWtlZg== 240w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/87lHukedjV_CuojmotOm38RXrY9ns4OlHJ2oU-Ddimo=/aHR0cHM6Ly9yZXMuY2xvdWRpbmFyeS5jb20vbGVzc3dyb25nLTItMC9pbWFnZS91cGxvYWQvZl9hdXRvLHFfYXV0by92MS9taXJyb3JlZEltYWdlcy82ZzhjQWZ0ZlF1ZkxtRkRZVC95YmJxYzd2dnJyYmZ6aXE2MGFreQ== 360w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/c8UYLt2Bgzn-f8LkNQ9waYov1jN22YVOlhiVAdpFAG4=/aHR0cHM6Ly9yZXMuY2xvdWRpbmFyeS5jb20vbGVzc3dyb25nLTItMC9pbWFnZS91cGxvYWQvZl9hdXRvLHFfYXV0by92MS9taXJyb3JlZEltYWdlcy82ZzhjQWZ0ZlF1ZkxtRkRZVC9tdGFrajhwdGVhbWlrcnJ3MW51YQ== 480w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/J3Go61oVL-ObCR3oyg-ZdsA6XSNt-BofYpy91jyG07Y=/aHR0cHM6Ly9yZXMuY2xvdWRpbmFyeS5jb20vbGVzc3dyb25nLTItMC9pbWFnZS91cGxvYWQvZl9hdXRvLHFfYXV0by92MS9taXJyb3JlZEltYWdlcy82ZzhjQWZ0ZlF1ZkxtRkRZVC9scDl0dHQ5anZsamRobmZlemN5YQ== 600w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/4RyRmtz-gw2oSevcIwr1HYbgaJgIcm8blVDx7SIlq58=/aHR0cHM6Ly9yZXMuY2xvdWRpbmFyeS5jb20vbGVzc3dyb25nLTItMC9pbWFnZS91cGxvYWQvZl9hdXRvLHFfYXV0by92MS9taXJyb3JlZEltYWdlcy82ZzhjQWZ0ZlF1ZkxtRkRZVC91cWp6cmhzend1dzBnZ3F0MXhwZg== 720w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/iW6G6B_XViG3Sy7E9iftUDyx5mltYRyroC_4GpGD1Dk=/aHR0cHM6Ly9yZXMuY2xvdWRpbmFyeS5jb20vbGVzc3dyb25nLTItMC9pbWFnZS91cGxvYWQvZl9hdXRvLHFfYXV0by92MS9taXJyb3JlZEltYWdlcy82ZzhjQWZ0ZlF1ZkxtRkRZVC9kMGJncHkybDZqbm55ZjBucXVncw== 840w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/5dZ_5qwoRATJl7iOGmO8O8SvZU0u4buH2fgNNRwQwm0=/aHR0cHM6Ly9yZXMuY2xvdWRpbmFyeS5jb20vbGVzc3dyb25nLTItMC9pbWFnZS91cGxvYWQvZl9hdXRvLHFfYXV0by92MS9taXJyb3JlZEltYWdlcy82ZzhjQWZ0ZlF1ZkxtRkRZVC9kczZkYm9kcnFjNGpnd3dpM3JoYg== 960w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/NBqnZ9wpOSYetSz1dtY7-CfMRrUa1AiMpljBTjiizAs=/aHR0cHM6Ly9yZXMuY2xvdWRpbmFyeS5jb20vbGVzc3dyb25nLTItMC9pbWFnZS91cGxvYWQvZl9hdXRvLHFfYXV0by92MS9taXJyb3JlZEltYWdlcy82ZzhjQWZ0ZlF1ZkxtRkRZVC9pNzNoaWN1Y2N4ZWNyenloZWU3eA== 1080w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/56YQdvimECDDt37gLhCehPWdYds1--yVwOhhTo3inCI=/aHR0cHM6Ly9yZXMuY2xvdWRpbmFyeS5jb20vbGVzc3dyb25nLTItMC9pbWFnZS91cGxvYWQvZl9hdXRvLHFfYXV0by92MS9taXJyb3JlZEltYWdlcy82ZzhjQWZ0ZlF1ZkxtRkRZVC93eXVmbXF5aWtxY3VmZTh4cTR1ZQ== 1182w" loading="lazy"/><figcaption><strong>A </strong><strong>cartoon</strong><strong> analogy for thinking about the learning process. </strong>In this toy landscape, there are two &#34;phases&#34; depicted by the orange and green projections. The <strong>orange phase</strong> is higher loss and more degenerate. The <strong>green phase</strong> is lower loss and less degenerate. As learning continues (<strong>left to right</strong>), we become less tolerant of high-loss solutions: the sea recedes, and we suddenly jump from the majority of the volume being occupied by the orange phase to the entirety of the volume being occupied by the green phase. In Bayesian learning, learning is dominated by transitions that lower loss and increase complexity. The link with SGD is an open question. </figcaption></figure><p>What we&#39;re interested in is the fraction of the surface area (=the volume of weight space) that is taken up by different kinds of solutions. At first, this surface area, and thus the behavior of our models, is dominated by the more degenerate solution at w1. </p><p>As we sample more data (n→∞) the sea starts to recede. When the sea level approaches the level of one of these highly degenerate, low-accuracy solutions, that solution suddenly and very rapidly loses a massive amount of surface area precisely because it is so degenerate. Shallow puddles vanish all at once. </p><p>The fraction of surface area taken up by successive, more complex solutions jumps just as suddenly and rapidly. There&#39;s a phase transition — a qualitative change in the kind and complexity of functions being learned.</p><p>The sea continues to sink. From where we&#39;re sitting — above the water — we can&#39;t see below the surface. We don&#39;t know where or when the next transition will take place. We hold our breaths...</p><h1>Estimating Learning Coefficients</h1><p>We&#39;ve seen what the learning coefficient is and how it measures the complexity of a model. But how can we go about practically estimating its value? In this section, we describe a set of techniques introduced by <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2308.12108" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">Lau et al. (2023)</a>.</p><h2>Deriving the Estimator</h2><p><strong>From free energies to learning coefficients. </strong>The free energy formula we saw earlier, </p>Fn→nLn(w∗)+λlogn+O(loglogn)asn→∞,<p>offers a means of calculating the learning coefficient. We simply shuffle the terms around to obtain:</p>λ→Fn−nLn(w∗)logn+O(loglognlogn).<p><strong>WBIC</strong>. Unfortunately, performing the integral required to evaluate Fn is intractable. As an alternative, we can consider the Widely Applicable Bayesian Information Criterion (WBIC), which generalizes the Bayesian Information Criterion (BIC) to singular models, </p>WBIC:=Eβ∗w[nLn(w)]=∫nLn(w)pβ∗(w|Dn)dw,<p>where pβ∗(w|Dn) is the <a href="http://arxiv.org/abs/1901.05353" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">tempered Bayesian posterior</a>,</p>pβ(w|Dn)=p(Dn|w)βφ(w)pβ(Dn),<p>sampled at inverse temperature β∗=1/logn <a href="https://www.jmlr.org/papers/volume14/watanabe13a/watanabe13a.pdf" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">(Watanabe, 2013)</a>. The two highest order terms in the expansion of the WBIC match that of the asymptotic expansion of Fn, which means we can substitute this in for Fn to estimate the learning coefficient:</p>^λ=Eβ∗w[nLn(w)]−nLn(w∗)logn.<p><strong>Expectations to empirical averages. </strong>To use this estimator, we need to first estimate the expectation value Eβ∗w[nLn(w)]. We can do this by sampling a set of weights Wβ∗={w1,…,wm|wi∼pβ∗(w|Dn)} and replacing the expectation value with an empirical average over the losses associated to those weights, </p>Eβ∗w[nLn(w)]≈1mm∑i=1nLn(wi).<p>Unfortunately, estimating Eβ∗w[nLn(w)] in practice runs into significant curse-of-dimensionality effects for systems at scale. </p><h2>The Local Learning Coefficient</h2><p><strong>From global to local.</strong> The problem becomes substantially more tractable if, instead of attempting to estimate the global learning coefficient, we estimate a local learning coefficient instead. We restrict our attention to a subset of weights and study how the volume scales in just that region. The scaling is dominated by the most complex local singularities. </p><p>As we saw in the aside on phase transitions, this local quantity is also more interesting from the perspective of dynamics. When actually training models, we don&#39;t care about the behaviors of all possible models, we care about the behavior of a specific model as it moves through the loss landscape.</p><figure><img src="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/inGAsV8M2fDa1VoBrsV1jBJWavW9ZptV_-w0JIulfBA=/aHR0cHM6Ly9yZXMuY2xvdWRpbmFyeS5jb20vbGVzc3dyb25nLTItMC9pbWFnZS91cGxvYWQvZl9hdXRvLHFfYXV0by92MS9taXJyb3JlZEltYWdlcy82ZzhjQWZ0ZlF1ZkxtRkRZVC9qaGNzc2RrdmZmZDIyd3huaW16aQ==" srcset="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/0cIJDOIV3qbNFmwdcW0Pm2XME62OUrfOf1QTBYN0KvA=/aHR0cHM6Ly9yZXMuY2xvdWRpbmFyeS5jb20vbGVzc3dyb25nLTItMC9pbWFnZS91cGxvYWQvZl9hdXRvLHFfYXV0by92MS9taXJyb3JlZEltYWdlcy82ZzhjQWZ0ZlF1ZkxtRkRZVC9kdW93eXduejRtM3FvYWF6ZHdwcQ== 156w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/FRXY9LAgzjXJu_37QBd3kc9SBSxPC97_DrjCqxDnATg=/aHR0cHM6Ly9yZXMuY2xvdWRpbmFyeS5jb20vbGVzc3dyb25nLTItMC9pbWFnZS91cGxvYWQvZl9hdXRvLHFfYXV0by92MS9taXJyb3JlZEltYWdlcy82ZzhjQWZ0ZlF1ZkxtRkRZVC96MmxjZmt5OGxkZWt5Ymx1bjlycg== 236w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/z5HtmocNM7v8hbbzr4kYqCUh8wXf_5LzLAUXUyH4QAQ=/aHR0cHM6Ly9yZXMuY2xvdWRpbmFyeS5jb20vbGVzc3dyb25nLTItMC9pbWFnZS91cGxvYWQvZl9hdXRvLHFfYXV0by92MS9taXJyb3JlZEltYWdlcy82ZzhjQWZ0ZlF1ZkxtRkRZVC95bWxqeHhuNGhxa240cXY1bzdwMw== 316w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/0EtS0lpKlahxn1dj51iEdOa6BTlLg2JjgM0iGv5xTz8=/aHR0cHM6Ly9yZXMuY2xvdWRpbmFyeS5jb20vbGVzc3dyb25nLTItMC9pbWFnZS91cGxvYWQvZl9hdXRvLHFfYXV0by92MS9taXJyb3JlZEltYWdlcy82ZzhjQWZ0ZlF1ZkxtRkRZVC9yZGJienRzaWIyYnBkbHBsM2s3bg== 396w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/Qg9Gn7Ssa_Z176e_xhX-8u9BjLqm8qLALL9ACOuxHZg=/aHR0cHM6Ly9yZXMuY2xvdWRpbmFyeS5jb20vbGVzc3dyb25nLTItMC9pbWFnZS91cGxvYWQvZl9hdXRvLHFfYXV0by92MS9taXJyb3JlZEltYWdlcy82ZzhjQWZ0ZlF1ZkxtRkRZVC9hY2J2bXY4b29lNHAzNmN0ZGxsYg== 476w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/Ekpa-ADRt7AMMFIoehlj-u1bH8wQRZ3efqU2mvVQv-0=/aHR0cHM6Ly9yZXMuY2xvdWRpbmFyeS5jb20vbGVzc3dyb25nLTItMC9pbWFnZS91cGxvYWQvZl9hdXRvLHFfYXV0by92MS9taXJyb3JlZEltYWdlcy82ZzhjQWZ0ZlF1ZkxtRkRZVC93c3VpZ2t3OGs0bXptZXZiNWR2Mg== 556w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/kCr_J030mOgB5d_jdeJX5L7D3-Rodc2UdkTq_ebmttc=/aHR0cHM6Ly9yZXMuY2xvdWRpbmFyeS5jb20vbGVzc3dyb25nLTItMC9pbWFnZS91cGxvYWQvZl9hdXRvLHFfYXV0by92MS9taXJyb3JlZEltYWdlcy82ZzhjQWZ0ZlF1ZkxtRkRZVC96bmlna3B5YnZtZ3dzdmtsZHZobg== 636w" loading="lazy"/><figcaption>Volume scaling restricted to a subset of weights is dominated by the local learning coefficient. </figcaption></figure><p><strong>The local learning coefficient. </strong>To estimate the local learning coefficient, Lau et al. (2023) replace the prior φ(w) with a localizing prior centered at the point ^w∗ whose learning coefficient we want to estimate:</p>φ(w)→φ(w−^w∗).<p>This ensures that samples drawn will remain &#34;close&#34; to the original point. Substituting this into the global ^λ estimator we saw earlier, we obtain the definition of the local learning coefficient,</p>^λ(^w∗)=Eβ∗w|^w∗[nLn(w)]−nLn(^w∗)logn,<p>known colloquially as &#34;<strong>lambda-hat</strong>,&#34; where Ew|^w∗ indicates the use of a localizing prior. </p><p>To estimate this expectation value, we compute an empirical average over the losses of a set of samples {wi}mi=1, now drawn from the localized posterior:</p>p(w|Dn,^w∗)∝p(Dn|w)φ(w−^w∗).<p>Given this empirical average, we plug it into the above formula for ^λ (subtracting n times the loss at ^w∗ and dividing by logn) to obtain an estimate for the local learning coefficient. </p><h2>Implementing the Estimator</h2><p><strong>How to localize?</strong> The first practical question we run into when implementing the local learning coefficient estimator is how to localize. Lau et al. consider a Gaussian prior parametrized by a scale γ. This is not the only possible choice, but it is perhaps the most straightforward choice: a gentle quadratic restoring force. </p><p><strong>How to sample? </strong>To draw samples from the posterior pβ∗(w|Dn,^w∗,γ), the natural thought is to use MCMC techniques. Explaining why these work is beyond the scope of this piece and is well covered elsewhere, but what&#39;s important here is that standard MCMC methods run into the curse of dimensionality, which makes them unsuitable for larger models. </p><figure><img src="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/1eBhyH9w2gbkkS4LAUyHCB3MUDC7zX8qzOg2D9Up82U=/aHR0cHM6Ly9yZXMuY2xvdWRpbmFyeS5jb20vbGVzc3dyb25nLTItMC9pbWFnZS91cGxvYWQvZl9hdXRvLHFfYXV0by92MS9taXJyb3JlZEltYWdlcy82ZzhjQWZ0ZlF1ZkxtRkRZVC9iNnlkeW1zZHp4bnJycmk3ODhpag==" srcset="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/MLgx4viuvmAwxrWsdkdQaijDsoxbRilXKWMItTXQh3Q=/aHR0cHM6Ly9yZXMuY2xvdWRpbmFyeS5jb20vbGVzc3dyb25nLTItMC9pbWFnZS91cGxvYWQvZl9hdXRvLHFfYXV0by92MS9taXJyb3JlZEltYWdlcy82ZzhjQWZ0ZlF1ZkxtRkRZVC95cnpjMnZkbXRzc210bHpld3NsdQ== 90w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/7biGAmo8Ho6yT_NY7SUyfzDrjdEjTGAQCOdyZd-68gE=/aHR0cHM6Ly9yZXMuY2xvdWRpbmFyeS5jb20vbGVzc3dyb25nLTItMC9pbWFnZS91cGxvYWQvZl9hdXRvLHFfYXV0by92MS9taXJyb3JlZEltYWdlcy82ZzhjQWZ0ZlF1ZkxtRkRZVC9ubjJ6bXkyMnd3MGNib3dvamdqYQ== 180w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/5w0NqEMAyM_4G9yClB1452CbB1Ycl8fzO3wgzG7ujJE=/aHR0cHM6Ly9yZXMuY2xvdWRpbmFyeS5jb20vbGVzc3dyb25nLTItMC9pbWFnZS91cGxvYWQvZl9hdXRvLHFfYXV0by92MS9taXJyb3JlZEltYWdlcy82ZzhjQWZ0ZlF1ZkxtRkRZVC9pYTdlcmFoandvbXR6bms3cWFoYw== 270w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/UFhg2ojXpDvc6XQh5QWwE_M-tiexSTSlLxi-zu2xjlM=/aHR0cHM6Ly9yZXMuY2xvdWRpbmFyeS5jb20vbGVzc3dyb25nLTItMC9pbWFnZS91cGxvYWQvZl9hdXRvLHFfYXV0by92MS9taXJyb3JlZEltYWdlcy82ZzhjQWZ0ZlF1ZkxtRkRZVC90MGllYmlhcDY4ZDNmcnp4YTV3NA== 360w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/ZEGww47AITUTLsz2Ds-dhfbLGTM2JhNdX-BlxC7OTXE=/aHR0cHM6Ly9yZXMuY2xvdWRpbmFyeS5jb20vbGVzc3dyb25nLTItMC9pbWFnZS91cGxvYWQvZl9hdXRvLHFfYXV0by92MS9taXJyb3JlZEltYWdlcy82ZzhjQWZ0ZlF1ZkxtRkRZVC9obWxhd21id2p3eDc0Y2dvY3Vhag== 450w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/04vpCv-O_6CDmVRvGom6QHIgeBo7fwTyF5Hs4GxIXaM=/aHR0cHM6Ly9yZXMuY2xvdWRpbmFyeS5jb20vbGVzc3dyb25nLTItMC9pbWFnZS91cGxvYWQvZl9hdXRvLHFfYXV0by92MS9taXJyb3JlZEltYWdlcy82ZzhjQWZ0ZlF1ZkxtRkRZVC9zZGYydWxvNmdzNm9zbGZobjVpbw== 540w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/TiP2hT_pe0TfRYBxrGzYigg187-o9A_TfOdKo59Ar9s=/aHR0cHM6Ly9yZXMuY2xvdWRpbmFyeS5jb20vbGVzc3dyb25nLTItMC9pbWFnZS91cGxvYWQvZl9hdXRvLHFfYXV0by92MS9taXJyb3JlZEltYWdlcy82ZzhjQWZ0ZlF1ZkxtRkRZVC9qbzFwdXpha3FpcGFoOTMxbnl0bQ== 630w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/CR0dt507xwBP_66RY1wJmkcS2pYUdKZ2Jf1GhkbgPxU=/aHR0cHM6Ly9yZXMuY2xvdWRpbmFyeS5jb20vbGVzc3dyb25nLTItMC9pbWFnZS91cGxvYWQvZl9hdXRvLHFfYXV0by92MS9taXJyb3JlZEl